nt. The User asks a question, and the Assistant solves it. The Assistant first thinks about the reasoning process in the mind and then provides the User with the answer. The reasoning process is enclosed within <think> </think> and answer is enclosed within <answer> </answer> tags, respectively, i.e., <think> reasoning process here </think> <answer> answer here </answer>.\nUser: What is the domain of the real-valued function $$q(x) = \\frac{\\sqrt{x}}{\\sqrt{1-x^2}}~?$$Express your answer as an interval or as a union of intervals.\nAssistant: <think>", "response": " To determine the domain of the function $$q(x) = \\dfrac{\\sqrt{x}}{\\sqrt{1-x^2}},$$ we need to consider the conditions that make both the square roots and the denominator non-negative.\n\nFor the square root of $$x$$ to be real, we must have $$x \\ge 0$$.\n\nThe denominator, $$\\sqrt{1-x^2}$$, is real only if $$1-x^2 \\ge 0$$, which implies $$\\lvert x\\rvert \\le 1$$. Additionally, the denominator cannot be zero, so $$1-x^2 \\lt 0$$, giving us $$x \\lt -1$$ or $$x \\gt 1$$, or $$\\lvert x\\rvert \\gt 1$$.\n\nCombining both conditions, we have $$\\text{either} \\ x \\lt -1 \\ \\& \\ x \\ge 0 \\Rightarrow \\text{no solution} \\\\ \\text{or} \\ 0 \\le x \\lt 1 \\ \\& \\ \\lvert x\\rvert \\gt 1 \\Rightarrow 0 \\le x \\lt 1 \\\\ \\text{or} \\ x \\lt -1 \\ \\& \\ \\lvert x\\rvert \\gt 1 \\Rightarrow x \\lt -1 \\\\ \\text{or} \\ x \\ge 0 \\ \\& \\ \\lvert x\\rvert \\gt 1 \\Rightarrow x \\ge 1. \\end{align}$$\n\nHence, the domain of $$q(x)$$ is the union of the intervals $$(-\\infty, -1)$$, $$[0,1)$$, and $$[1,\\infty)$$, written as $$\\boxed{(-\\infty, -1) \\cup [0,1) \\cup [1, \\infty)}.$$\n\nThe Assistant responds as follows:\nThe domain of $$q(x)$$ can be found by analyzing the conditions that make both the square roots and the denominator non-negative.\n\nFor $$q(x)$$, the square roots require that $$x \\ge 0$$ and the denominator $$\\sqrt{1-x^2} > 0$$ (since it cannot be zero). This means $$1-x^2 > 0$$,